04317nam a22005415i 9780773550032DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735500327 a10.1515/97807735500322doi  a(DE-B1597)654709  a(OCoLC)962129452  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDK266b.R32 2017eb 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a303.48/52231 aRaab, Nigel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAll Shook Up :bThe Shifting Soviet Response to Catastrophes, 1917-1991 /cNigel Raab. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b6 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tConceptualizing Disasters -- tDisorder in the Orderly Stalinist World -- tThe Crimean Peninsula in September 1927 and Ashgabat in October 1948 -- tThe Mobilization of Soviet Society under Brezhnev -- tApril 1966: Tashkent in the News -- tApril 1966: Tashkent in the Streets -- tVisualizing Soviet Disasters from 1945 to 1986 -- tAging Response Models in Gorbachev's New World -- tApril 1986: Chernobyl -- tDecember 1988: Armenia -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarthquakes, nuclear accidents, and floods were among the many unexpected tragedies that struck the Soviet Union over its history. Requiring the immediate mobilization of vast resources and aid, and embedded within a specific context and time, these catastrophes provide critical insights into the nature of the twentieth-century Communist state. All Shook Up takes a close look at the representation in film, the political repercussions, and the social opportunities of large-scale catastrophes in separate Soviet epochs, including the 1927 earthquake in the Crimean peninsula, the 1948 earthquake in Ashgabat, the Tashkent earthquake in 1966, the Chernobyl explosion in 1986, and the Armenian earthquake in 1988. Juxtaposing various disaster responses and demonstrating the ways both Soviet authorities and citizens molded them to their own cultural needs, Nigel Raab highlights the radical shifts in disaster policy from one leader to the next. Given the opportunity to act outside regular parameters, Soviet residents not only rebuilt their devastated cities, but also experimented with new values and crafted their own worldview while the state struggled to return the situation to normal. Based on archival research conducted in Russia and Ukraine, All Shook Up fills a gap in a global literature and challenges stereotypical representations of the Soviet Union as a monolithic state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDisastersxPolitical aspectszSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aDisastersxSocial aspectszSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aDisasterszSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355003240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773550032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773550032/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles